Subsidy trap
The United States' Cambridge – no policy has pitted good economics against good politics as directly as food and energy subsidies have.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue faced by three of the world's most important new leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Jokowi, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi's need for subsidy cuts is somewhat better than expected.
Contrary to expectations, Modi faces an even worse situation, which could potentially jeopardize the long-awaited WTO agreement.
Contrary to expectations, Jokowi's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved a feat that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have been able to accomplish: he significantly reduced the long-standing energy subsidies, leading to prices rising by 41-78%.
It's surprising that almost no anti-protest demonstrations took place.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have long been kept at extremely low levels, often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut back on such subsidies often sparked unrest, and in some cases even led to regime change.
But the Sisi regime seems to have made progress in this area as well.
The bread subsidy has been reduced by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Even with the subsidy reduction, the current regime's next fiscal year's budget deficit target still reached 10% of GDP (which would have been 14% without the subsidy reduction).
However, almost no one anticipated that Sisi, who came to power in a tumultuous political environment, would act more swiftly than Modi. Modi ascended to the prime ministership of India, which has been eager for comprehensive economic reform, by a landslide democratic majority.
In Indonesia, President Jokowi, who took office in October, inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy, worth $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government expenditures), which has put the country under unsustainable pressure.
The outgoing Suharto had taken a bold step a year ago by increasing fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommend cutting the remaining subsidies, and he bluntly states that he plans to gradually implement the plan over the next four years.
Economists are confident in their opposition to commodity subsidies because the agricultural and energy markets are nearly perfectly competitive, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive fields, the regime – rather than large private monopolies – is the source.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For instance, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
It is the contentious nature of food and fossil fuel subsidies that they are often justified under the guise of environmental or egalitarian concerns, but in reality, they fail to address these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Egypt's food subsidies only benefit the poor by less than 20%.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies have benefited the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, only less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies reach the most impoverished populations, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the wealthiest groups.
In the world at large, only a small fraction less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
The Modi regime, which aims to protect India's agricultural subsidies, is a clear case in point of how food and energy subsidies can distort public policy.
In fact, the Modi regime vetoed the WTO compromise, thus destroying the most important progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, particularly in poor countries; at other times, they benefit consumers at the expense of producers, particularly in rich countries.
India's policies aim to strike a balance.
As a result, India achieved a feat: distributing wheat to consumers at prices that are lower for the people, while also experiencing an over-supply, as farmers can obtain high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs -- electricity, water, and fertilizers -- but the environment is damaged as a result.)
The regime has been buying large quantities of rotten rice and wheat, while the distribution of a small portion to consumers is both corrupt and fails to meet the goal of helping the poor.
The regime may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
But it knows that this will contravene WTO rules.
Since it is impossible to permanently alter these rules, Modi simply vetoed the WTO's eagerly anticipated Trade Facilitation Agreement.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are difficult to reverse.
When global commodity prices surge (as they did over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot insulate them from the shock.
But citizens accustomed to government-determined food and energy prices will demand that the regime be held accountable.
This constitutes a strong argument that subsidies should never have been implemented in the first place.
But this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining subsidies is always the shrewdest choice for savvy politicians.
If the alternative to price hikes is shortages or rationing, angry opponents are also likely to erupt.
Similarly, if an ever-widening gap ultimately leads to even greater retail price hikes, sluggish leaders will hardly benefit from the delay.
In ideal circumstances, while reducing food and energy subsidies, more efficient measures to support low-income earners should be taken instead.
Developing countries have had considerable experience in developing effective transfer mechanisms, including innovative conditional cash transfer programs such as Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations such as India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries are only forced to adjust when a budget crisis arrives, and they may not have the funds available for transfers to alleviate the pain.
Savvy politicians may well have to implement unpopular adjustments from the start of their tenure.
Jokowi and Sisi both adopted this policy.
But Modi, who won a landslide victory in elections under the banner of market reform, has fallen behind.
